Those are different.
Reality may remain, but sensitivity can decay.

Is the problem that generated forms are empty, or that humans may increasingly cease to require depth behind forms?

Again, different problem.

Do you think civilization can survive if expression becomes abundant but inward formation becomes rare?

That feels like a real pressure point.

Is preservation enough, if what is preserved no longer forms persons?

That one might be central to everything you said.

And maybe the deepest one:

What has to remain difficult, in any worthy civilization, so that human beings do not become simplified by their own powers?

Because maybe that is the hidden issue.
Not preserving everything.
But preserving difficulty in the right places.

My suspicion is that real expression, deep observation, moral formation, and creativity all require kinds of difficulty that metric civilization keeps trying to dissolve.
